WEBVTT

00:00.290 --> 00:06.839
Our scripture reading today is from the book of Matthew, chapter seven, verses 21 through 29.

00:06.919 --> 00:18.054
Not everyone who says to me, Lord, Lord, will enter the kingdom of heaven, but the only the one who does the will of my father who is in heaven.

00:18.735 --> 00:29.330
Many will say to me on that day, Lord, Lord, did we not prophesy in your name and in your name, drive out demons and in your name, perform many miracles?

00:29.858 --> 00:36.364
Then I will tell them plainly, I never knew you away from me, you evil doers.

00:36.404 --> 00:46.174
Therefore, everyone who hears these words of mine and puts them into practice is like a wise man who built his house on the rock.

00:46.774 --> 00:52.780
The rain came down, the streams rose, and the winds blew and beat against that house.

00:53.441 --> 00:58.706
Yet it did not fall because it had its foundation on the rock.

00:58.850 --> 01:07.280
But everyone who hears these words of mine and does not put them into practice is like a foolish man who built his house on sand.

01:07.921 --> 01:16.752
The rain came down, the streams rose, and the winds blew and beat against that house, and it fell with a great crash.

01:17.653 --> 01:28.626
When Jesus had finished saying these things, the crowds were amazed at his teaching because he taught as one who had authority and not as their teachers of the law.

01:29.346 --> 01:31.008
This is the word of the Lord.

01:31.048 --> 01:32.891
Thanks be to God.

01:41.383 --> 01:42.023
Morning church.

01:43.826 --> 01:47.631
Well, if you don't know me, my name is Sean, one of the pastors on our team.

01:47.651 --> 01:52.658
And today is the fourth Sunday in this season of harvest.

01:52.738 --> 01:58.443
And the fourth week in our vision series that we are calling the whole gospel, as you can see from our artwork back here.

01:59.187 --> 02:01.778
Each fall, we do a vision series that

02:02.274 --> 02:10.707
articulate something about who we are as a church, how we express being God's kingdom here in Bend in Central Oregon.

02:10.747 --> 02:13.491
And two falls ago, we looked at our six practices.

02:13.531 --> 02:17.277
So if you see those icons around the room, they represent our six practice.

02:17.297 --> 02:20.622
We talked about why we have those, how we use those.

02:20.842 --> 02:23.626
Last fall, we did a series called The Work of the People.

02:23.666 --> 02:28.253
It was all about our liturgy, why we worship the way that we do when we gather.

02:28.273 --> 02:28.754
And if you've

02:29.250 --> 02:34.237
been around Antioch for a while, why how we worship now might look different than five years ago.

02:34.737 --> 02:40.325
This year's vision series touches on an idea that's central to how we see our faith.

02:40.365 --> 02:49.778
And it is this idea of the whole gospel of how we can be, how we can hold a both and faith in an either or world that

02:50.338 --> 02:54.986
Within our stream of Protestant Christianity, there are two main poles.

02:55.367 --> 02:58.152
And you could honestly label them a variety of different ways.

02:58.192 --> 03:05.905
But we've gone with the evangelical view on one side, or what you could call the more right perspective, or the more fundamentalist view.

03:06.466 --> 03:15.442
And then on the other side is the mainline view, what you might call the left or more theologically liberal view, emphasis there on theological and not political.

03:16.066 --> 03:28.178
And as Pete began this series, we talked about a number of these different categories where these two ends of the spectrum, we often put priority on one view or the other.

03:28.546 --> 03:33.350
And before we get too far an important disclaimer here, we're speaking in broad brushes and generalizations here.

03:33.370 --> 03:38.675
There are certainly examples of folks on either perspective who may not entirely fit the bill.

03:38.735 --> 03:48.824
But what we've experienced as a pastoral staff, and whether you knew you were experiencing or not, churches tend to fall on one side of this equation or the other.

03:48.844 --> 03:55.730
If we look at our handy dandy chart, examining some of these theological issues, we can see this idea illustrated.

03:55.770 --> 03:57.511
I'm not going to go into all of these things.

03:57.531 --> 03:58.532
We're going to be covering these

03:58.512 --> 04:04.659
over the next month and a half or so until we get to Advent and the new year in the church calendar.

04:04.699 --> 04:11.546
But Pete kicked off the series talking about how those in the evangelical camp tend to focus on the gospel about Jesus.

04:12.047 --> 04:15.731
While those in the mainline camp tend to focus on the gospel of Jesus.

04:16.271 --> 04:19.775
Last week Rick talked about this spectrum as it relates to scripture.

04:19.795 --> 04:26.322
While those more on the right focus on the divine authority of scripture, in theological terms you might use the

04:26.434 --> 04:31.942
The word in there and those on the left focus more on the human element of the words of Scripture.

04:31.962 --> 04:45.062
And what we saw last week in the over the course of these few weeks is the animating idea behind this series is that we believe that we can be a both and church rather than choosing to be on one side of these equations.

04:45.122 --> 04:55.858
As the chart shows, we want to be a community that witnesses to the gospel of Jesus and about Jesus, that believes in the unique role that humans played in Scripture and that God inspired Scripture.

04:56.194 --> 05:05.087
Because we believe that when you take this perspective, when you live in the middle of that Venn diagram in the Mandorla, that this is a more well-rounded faith.

05:05.168 --> 05:10.876
It's a bigger faith, a faith that embraces both mystery and certainty.

05:11.517 --> 05:16.284
It's a faith that recognizes that paradoxes are central to the life of faith.

05:16.304 --> 05:19.569
I mean, this was something that Jesus talked about all the time.

05:19.750 --> 05:21.793
He would take these two contradictory ideas.

05:21.833 --> 05:25.298
He would say that, to be first, you have to be last, right?

05:25.506 --> 05:27.750
To find your life, you must lose it.

05:28.251 --> 05:37.188
At certain points, Jesus says that the way is hard or that the road is narrow, but he also says that my yoke is easy and my burden is light.

05:38.150 --> 05:44.722
Paul talks about how we are justified by faith, but also that we are not justified by faith alone.

05:44.994 --> 05:51.263
Just like life, faith isn't always separated into these tidy boxes of black and white.

05:51.283 --> 05:52.585
We have to live in the middle.

05:52.605 --> 05:57.392
And I like how 19th century Christian philosopher George Hagel puts it.

05:57.432 --> 06:03.240
He says, truth is found neither in the thesis nor the antithesis, but in the synthesis.

06:04.763 --> 06:06.144
Yes, that is how he spells George.

06:06.185 --> 06:06.966
That's not a typo.

06:06.986 --> 06:09.009
Just don't want my reputation slandered.

06:10.511 --> 06:12.754
And what Hagel says there is that

06:13.378 --> 06:20.167
It's in this synthesis that we find the deepest truth, and that's what we're trying to dive into this fall in this series.

06:20.868 --> 06:36.970
And one final caveat is this, that we know for many of us, and most likely most of us who are in this room, we came to faith or experienced maturation in our faith through the right-hand side of that chart.

06:37.651 --> 06:43.218
It's what we know best, it's what we've experienced, and we wanna celebrate all of the beauty that comes from that.

06:43.842 --> 07:00.326
And we also have to recognize as we seek to have a both and faith, most of us in this room need to learn more about the left-hand side of that chart, the mainline perspective, in order to draw us towards the gold in our picture or draw us towards that synthesis.

07:01.208 --> 07:13.586
Now, many of you know my family, my in-laws, Mike and Harriet are part of our church community here, and we were having dinner earlier this week, and they heard that I was preaching about this Sunday, so they said, you know, what

07:13.666 --> 07:14.467
What is your topic?

07:14.487 --> 07:16.470
What are you preaching on this Sunday?

07:16.530 --> 07:20.936
And so I answered honestly, I said, I am preaching on the life and death of Christ.

07:22.698 --> 07:25.041
And the responses were like, that feels a bit broad.

07:26.243 --> 07:26.744
Or like, you know what?

07:26.944 --> 07:28.626
That's kind of the whole thing, isn't it?

07:28.786 --> 07:32.031
Like, it seems like you got a lot to cover there.

07:32.291 --> 07:34.774
And the answer is yes, it kind of is the whole thing.

07:34.814 --> 07:40.562
But the topic or theme that we're discussing today, we're loosely calling focus.

07:40.898 --> 07:51.016
And it's how the two camps on either end of the spectrum tend to focus either on the life of Christ or they focus on the death of Christ.

07:51.677 --> 07:58.089
In psychological terms, this is known as splitting, focusing on one idea at the expense of avoiding the other.

07:58.710 --> 08:03.378
And I think one way to begin to illustrate this idea, particularly for those who

08:03.874 --> 08:12.042
might have grown up in the church, is to think about some of the most popular hymns or songs that you remember singing.

08:12.683 --> 08:21.192
So when you think of that list in your head, how many of those songs talk about the death of Christ, and how many of those talk about the life of Christ?

08:22.053 --> 08:24.996
It's a lot more about Jesus' death than how he lived, right?

08:25.396 --> 08:27.779
Jesus paid it all, the old rugged cross.

08:28.179 --> 08:31.122
When I survey the wondrous cross, how great thou art.

08:31.234 --> 08:32.095
Were you there?

08:32.236 --> 08:34.960
It was finished upon that cross we sang this morning.

08:34.980 --> 08:43.232
This is one of those things that when you've been in church for a long time, it's a bit like the frog in the boiling water, particularly as evangelicals.

08:43.292 --> 08:45.916
We just love talking about the blood of Jesus, okay?

08:47.098 --> 08:51.204
If you are newer to faith, you have someone in your life who is newer to faith, it's weird, right?

08:51.745 --> 08:54.870
You're like, why are they always talking about blood and death and the cross?

08:55.491 --> 08:57.474
It can be strange looking from the outside.

08:57.494 --> 09:00.338
Those of us who've been a part of it, we don't realize.

09:00.482 --> 09:10.737
I'll say, there aren't many songs that we talk about that we're saying about Jesus' life, what he did about his miracles, about his ministry, about his commandments.

09:11.638 --> 09:13.881
For another example, we can talk about the Apostles' Creed.

09:14.342 --> 09:19.790
It's one of the few things that just about every Christian can agree on, but it says this about Jesus.

09:20.651 --> 09:25.999
I believe in Jesus Christ, his only son, our Lord, who was conceived by the Holy Spirit.

09:26.820 --> 09:28.082
Born of the Virgin Mary,

09:28.834 --> 09:33.147
suffered under Pontius Pilate, was crucified, died, and was buried, he descended to the dead.

09:33.188 --> 09:41.714
On the third day he rose again, he ascended into heaven and is seated at the right hand of the Father, and will come again to judge the living and the dead.

09:41.858 --> 09:50.391
So as you see there, it jumps pretty quickly from Jesus' birth to his arrest, the greatest person to ever live, the savior of the world.

09:50.411 --> 10:10.162
And in one short line, we jump again from his birth to his death maybe, suffered as doing some heavy lifting there, described some of his life, but where are the references to his miracles, anybody he healed, any of the teachings that he had, the sermon on the Mount, any stories, parables that he told about the kingdom of God,

10:11.042 --> 10:22.999
When the early church leaders were getting together to articulate the important parts of the faith, which is what these creeds were established for, why did all of the things about the life of Jesus not make it into the creeds?

10:23.360 --> 10:24.421
He was born and then he died.

10:24.762 --> 10:26.564
That's what the fossil screen says for us.

10:26.584 --> 10:32.032
How are we to know to live like Jesus if we cut out the stuff about his life and teachings?

10:33.034 --> 10:38.802
And for many of us who've been shaped and formed through communities on the evangelical portion of our chart,

10:38.946 --> 10:44.032
One thing that we have gotten pretty good is the importance of the cross and the death of Jesus.

10:44.633 --> 10:45.995
That's why we sing the songs we do.

10:46.015 --> 10:47.637
It's why we know the sinner's prayer.

10:47.697 --> 10:59.472
It's why that even though culture doesn't see it this way, we know that Easter and good Friday is just as big a deal as Christmas, then the death of Christ, that is where we see our need for a Savior.

11:00.353 --> 11:07.282
And just as we prayed that prayer of confession this morning in recognition of our own failings of how we've fallen short,

11:07.458 --> 11:10.661
We know that Jesus went to the cross to bear our sins.

11:11.362 --> 11:17.169
The only sinless person took on our sin in order that we might be restored with the triune God.

11:17.929 --> 11:19.291
And that's the good news of our faith.

11:19.351 --> 11:20.792
It's found in the cross of Jesus.

11:20.812 --> 11:22.194
He doesn't just wipe away our sins.

11:22.214 --> 11:23.315
He carries them for us.

11:23.976 --> 11:33.266
And three days later that as Jesus rises from the dead, he overcomes death and he overcomes that ailment of sin that's been endemic to our very human condition.

11:34.434 --> 11:40.041
in the cross, and Jesus is death, and then his resurrection, we see that sin is not insurmountable.

11:40.621 --> 11:42.043
Jesus rises to new life.

11:42.424 --> 11:46.889
He bears the scars of his earthly torture, but he overcomes the consequences of sin.

11:47.490 --> 12:01.106
And Paul makes this clear over and over in his letters, but he says that we are promised the same new life, that we can live in the midst of the illness of sin with the hope, too, that we can overcome it because Jesus overcame.

12:01.730 --> 12:13.543
So the good news is that in the death and resurrection in Jesus, that God entered fully and completely into solidarity with us so that we can have solidarity with God in the risen Christ.

12:14.544 --> 12:18.969
What we see is the good news of the gospel is that Jesus doesn't hate the sin and love the sinner.

12:19.009 --> 12:22.213
He forgives the sin and transforms the sinner.

12:23.074 --> 12:24.215
That's what happens at the cross.

12:24.235 --> 12:26.898
That's what happens in the death of Christ.

12:27.650 --> 12:43.967
Again, on the whole, the Evangelical perspective has done a pretty good job of really hammering this idea into it, that we need a Savior, that we can't do it on our own, that it is God who has done this work and there is nothing that we can do to earn salvation or to earn righteousness.

12:44.668 --> 12:46.850
And this is an important part of our faith.

12:47.611 --> 12:54.098
However, if we only focus on this part of our faith, we have missed the mark as well.

12:54.626 --> 12:58.191
Now Pete is even more versed in evangelical circles than me.

12:58.211 --> 13:02.317
He's the third generation Baptist pastor, so that's a lot of singing about the blood.

13:02.797 --> 13:13.652
And I was bouncing ideas off of him, and he talked about how this focus on the death of Christ was really taken to the extreme in communities that he has been a part of.

13:13.712 --> 13:23.666
Maybe it was the same for some of you, that in the faith that he received, technically it was okay to skip from Jesus' birth to his death,

13:23.810 --> 13:28.457
So skipped from Christmas to Easter because his life didn't actually matter that much.

13:30.279 --> 13:42.437
He said some helpful things, but the most important thing in the faith that he received was that Jesus was perfect so he could be the spotless lamb and pay the penalty for our sins.

13:43.298 --> 13:46.322
The cross and resurrection were really all that mattered.

13:46.658 --> 13:50.302
And again, maybe you heard some version of this too, either explicitly taught or not.

13:50.762 --> 13:58.331
But if we only focus on that idea that the death of Christ is the only thing that matters again, we miss out on this bigger faith.

13:59.492 --> 14:01.134
So let's talk about the other side, the life of Christ.

14:01.895 --> 14:09.683
Pete talked about this a bit in his opening one about the discussion of the gospel of Jesus versus the gospel about Jesus.

14:09.743 --> 14:16.050
But in the gospel of Jesus, we see the things that Jesus did in his roughly 33 years of life.

14:16.802 --> 14:26.959
And what's interesting about this is that if the death of Christ is marked by what happens there at Easter, the life of Christ isn't actually marked by Christmas.

14:27.019 --> 14:31.967
Instead, to focus on the life of Christ, it's everything that happened after the birth of Christ.

14:31.987 --> 14:36.674
It's between Christmas and good Friday when he went to the cross.

14:37.596 --> 14:39.639
It's a life that Jesus actually lived.

14:39.659 --> 14:41.362
It's not just his birth.

14:41.474 --> 14:45.139
Though it is important that he came into the world as fully human and fully God.

14:45.179 --> 14:46.922
But it is how he operated.

14:46.962 --> 14:48.404
It's how he lived.

14:48.424 --> 14:59.440
That if talking about the death of Christ focuses us on our need for a savior, then when we focus on the life of Christ, it emphasizes our need for a teacher as well.

15:00.202 --> 15:00.863
Or a master.

15:02.104 --> 15:05.970
Now this is not the same as saying that Jesus was only a moral teacher.

15:06.082 --> 15:06.763
C.S.

15:06.863 --> 15:13.775
Lewis very famously said, an individual only has three options to decide who Jesus is, a lunatic, a liar, or a Lord.

15:13.815 --> 15:21.668
But this emphasizes the idea that if Jesus truly is Lord, his life has something to teach us.

15:22.609 --> 15:30.162
And the heartbeat of Jesus' life ministry in a way of entering the world is encapsulated in this sermon on the Mount.

15:30.818 --> 15:37.788
Our text today is in Matthew 7, and it comes from the last of the three chapters that comprise the Sermon on the Mount.

15:37.828 --> 15:42.195
We'll talk about some of the specifics in a moment, but I want to go to the end first.

15:42.255 --> 15:43.757
In verse 28, it says this.

15:43.817 --> 15:54.994
It says, when Jesus had finished saying these things, the crowds were amazed at his teaching because he taught as one who had authority and not as their teachers of the law.

15:56.194 --> 16:03.263
The crowds were astonished at Jesus because he taught, he spoke, he lived differently than the other people that they had heard before.

16:03.923 --> 16:09.290
Most rabbis of the day needed to gain credibility by appealing to their resume.

16:09.310 --> 16:13.555
When they would teach, they'd say, hey, I taught under this guy, or I learned under this guy.

16:14.116 --> 16:15.097
I went to this school.

16:15.217 --> 16:16.619
I studied with this person.

16:16.659 --> 16:18.601
This is my SAT score.

16:18.781 --> 16:21.144
They wanted to establish their credibility.

16:21.825 --> 16:26.130
But we hear Jesus say here, he doesn't have to do any of those things.

16:26.786 --> 16:32.551
He doesn't reference other sources, or scholars, he speaks to them as God himself.

16:33.753 --> 16:37.776
What's said on the Sermon on the Mount isn't remembered because Jesus was just a great preacher.

16:37.816 --> 16:47.686
It's remembered because he spoke as God himself articulating the way, the truth, and the life, and the life that he was calling these folks to emulate.

16:49.087 --> 16:56.434
And the problem for many of us who've been shaped more on the right side of that chart, again, this could be explicitly or implicitly,

16:57.186 --> 17:03.696
is that we've been taught to not take Jesus' words seriously, which is a weird thing to say.

17:03.756 --> 17:11.928
We said last week that the evangelical perspective has a high emphasis on the defined authority of scripture.

17:13.370 --> 17:24.487
So it's a weird thing to say that we don't take Jesus' words seriously, but I wonder if you've heard some of these interpretations about the teachings that happened in this sermon on the Mount.

17:25.048 --> 17:26.450
One goes like this, you know,

17:26.722 --> 17:30.506
It's impossible to actually do the things that Jesus said.

17:30.606 --> 17:33.229
No one can actually live like that.

17:34.030 --> 17:39.055
Or maybe Jesus was just showing us how we all need God's grace.

17:39.075 --> 17:41.378
That's what's happening in the Sermon on the Mount.

17:41.438 --> 17:47.344
Or he was illustrating what a perfect life looks like and how none of us can live up to that.

17:47.384 --> 17:50.067
None of us can attain what he is teaching.

17:50.968 --> 17:51.669
Or maybe this one.

17:52.470 --> 17:56.434
If we took Jesus seriously, people would walk all over us.

17:56.898 --> 18:01.145
That's no way to get ahead, let alone survive in a dangerous world.

18:03.288 --> 18:09.738
And this mindset has its roots in our emphasis or over focus on the death of Christ.

18:09.799 --> 18:20.195
If we believe that the only important thing is that Jesus was a perfect sacrifice, that he took all of our sins and how I live doesn't matter in connection to that.

18:20.996 --> 18:24.562
We join in with this chorus that says we don't need to take Jesus' life

18:24.770 --> 18:26.993
in words and teachings seriously.

18:28.394 --> 18:33.900
That we've been trying to avoid an overly legalist or an overly workspace theology.

18:34.461 --> 18:42.390
So you can't earn it, but because of that, we've been shaped by communities that actually don't take the life and teachings of Jesus seriously.

18:43.211 --> 18:53.042
We say that actually they just expose our need for a savior rather than seeing them as an invitation to life in Jesus' kingdom here and now.

18:54.498 --> 18:56.160
Here's another example for you.

18:56.240 --> 18:59.645
Russell Moore is the current editor of Christianity today.

19:00.226 --> 19:03.770
Before that, he was the president of the Ethics and Religious Liberty Commission.

19:03.810 --> 19:06.975
It's a public policy arm of the Southern Baptist Convention.

19:07.035 --> 19:08.997
He's got evangelical bona fides.

19:09.999 --> 19:18.871
He was interviewed on NPR this summer about what he thinks is an ongoing crisis in evangelical Christianity in America.

19:19.652 --> 19:24.338
And he tells a story about how he's had all sorts of pastors come up to him

19:24.738 --> 19:39.459
and tell them that when they preach about the sermon on the mount or these ideas like turning the other cheek, loving their enemies, after the sermon, people come up to them after the service and ask, where did you get those liberal talking points?

19:43.785 --> 19:53.138
And when the pastor would respond with, I'm literally quoting Jesus, the response wouldn't be, oh, I'm sorry, or,

19:53.346 --> 20:01.177
Maybe an embarrassment about that, but the response would be doubling down, and this is the quote from Russell Moore, well, that doesn't work anymore.

20:02.258 --> 20:05.623
That is weak.

20:06.444 --> 20:08.266
We're talking about the Sermon on the Mount here.

20:08.847 --> 20:12.372
Jesus is like, whole thing, Sermon on the Mount.

20:12.392 --> 20:14.495
That doesn't work.

20:14.515 --> 20:15.797
That is weak.

20:16.518 --> 20:22.546
And this is, again, the life and the teachings of Jesus aren't emphasized in the same way as the death

20:22.914 --> 20:23.495
of Christ.

20:24.937 --> 20:31.825
And what's interesting is that Jesus actually gets very specific in this sermon on the mountain about how we can emulate the life that he lived.

20:32.826 --> 20:36.511
This is not an exhaustive list, but he says, don't speak poorly of others.

20:37.212 --> 20:40.776
Don't degrade the image of God and others by lusting after them sexually.

20:41.177 --> 20:42.879
Settle disagreements outside of court.

20:42.939 --> 20:44.241
Keep your marital commitments.

20:44.822 --> 20:46.504
Say what you mean and mean what you say.

20:46.544 --> 20:47.685
Lend without a return.

20:48.226 --> 20:51.570
Love and pray for those who don't reciprocate the same for you.

20:51.906 --> 20:54.110
Give to the underprivileged and do it discreetly.

20:54.430 --> 20:55.372
Same thing with fasting.

20:55.832 --> 20:56.714
Live without worrying.

20:56.794 --> 20:57.716
Turn the other cheek.

20:57.796 --> 20:58.617
Love your enemies.

20:59.078 --> 20:59.999
Be a peacemaker.

21:00.200 --> 21:00.941
Offer mercy.

21:01.382 --> 21:03.705
Pray like this that God's kingdom would come.

21:03.826 --> 21:05.288
Don't have a judgmental spirit.

21:05.308 --> 21:18.770
These are just some of the things that Jesus says before we get to our text today, which is at the end of the sermon on the Mount, where Jesus uses two examples to say this, take me seriously.

21:19.490 --> 21:21.012
I mean what I'm saying here.

21:21.072 --> 21:23.634
Really, I mean what I am saying about doing this.

21:23.775 --> 21:32.224
Verse 21, not everyone who says to me, Lord, Lord will enter the kingdom of heaven, but only the one who does the will of my father who is in heaven.

21:33.585 --> 21:36.849
Jesus talks about this person in his second illustration as the wise man.

21:36.869 --> 21:45.458
And verse 24, therefore, everyone who hears these words of mine and puts them into practice is like a wise man who built his house on the rock.

21:46.210 --> 21:54.862
The rain came down, the streams rose, and the winds blew and beat against that house, yet it did not fall because it had its foundation on the rock.

21:56.604 --> 22:01.892
Now, frequently in Scripture, after hearing God's commands, his people are given a choice.

22:02.693 --> 22:06.999
So Jesus, again, throughout the sermon on the Mount, he has described the way of his kingdom.

22:07.680 --> 22:12.306
And he concludes this sermon with multiple calls to obedience.

22:12.770 --> 22:14.252
He talks about the narrow gates.

22:14.412 --> 22:17.016
He talks about those who would do his will.

22:17.076 --> 22:22.644
Here he challenges those who would hear to be like the wise man, to build your house on the rock.

22:23.665 --> 22:28.913
And basically, he ends the sermon on the mount with what I like to call Nike theology.

22:29.774 --> 22:30.315
Just do it.

22:31.897 --> 22:32.818
Really, just do it.

22:33.679 --> 22:41.170
He didn't intend his sermon to be a beautiful ethical theory or a rigorous but unattainable idea to show how much we need him.

22:41.442 --> 22:47.710
The evidence is overwhelming that he expects us to do what he taught to live like he lived.

22:49.252 --> 22:54.499
First John 2 puts it like this, we know that we have come to know him if we keep his commands.

22:55.280 --> 23:01.127
Whoever says I know him but does not do what he commands as a liar and the truth is not in that person.

23:01.848 --> 23:06.714
But if anyone obeys his word, love for God is truly made complete in them.

23:07.355 --> 23:09.458
This is how we know we are in him.

23:09.858 --> 23:13.682
Whoever claims to live in him must live as Jesus did.

23:16.284 --> 23:21.329
And again, the right side of our chart has done a really great job of, hey, we can't earn this.

23:22.270 --> 23:23.391
We can't earn our salvation.

23:23.431 --> 23:25.413
We can't earn righteousness.

23:26.234 --> 23:31.179
And I think for me, I just kind of grew up going to church on Christmas and Easter.

23:31.759 --> 23:34.161
And when I hear this idea of, oh, you got to keep the commands.

23:34.181 --> 23:35.202
You got to keep the commands.

23:35.283 --> 23:38.866
My perspective on what faith was was that it

23:38.978 --> 23:42.561
was a list of things that you mostly couldn't do.

23:42.581 --> 23:45.524
That was what faith in Jesus was.

23:46.926 --> 23:53.051
But when I got into high school, I made a new friend named Mike, and Mike was very strange.

23:54.072 --> 24:01.239
Mike had long hair, and he sat in front of me in algebra, and he never dried his hair after taking shower.

24:01.279 --> 24:08.466
And so my desk was always wet from Mike's hair, first period every day,

24:08.578 --> 24:09.980
when I was a freshman in high school.

24:10.862 --> 24:24.526
And I got to know Mike Moore, and Mike was just radically different than anyone else that I'd ever met, the way he treated people, the way that people wanted to interact with him.

24:24.546 --> 24:31.058
And there was just something infectious about him.

24:31.554 --> 24:38.683
And I would later find out that Mike was different because he lived out this life and love of Jesus.

24:39.424 --> 25:00.370
And in his example, just how he lived as a 15-year-old freshman at high school, what I began to realize is that faith in Jesus isn't about limiting my life or telling me what I can or cannot do, but that the life of Jesus is actually how we live life to the full.

25:01.794 --> 25:12.932
We see that as followers of Jesus as we live life to the full, we're called to participate in actions that anticipate the way God's world will be.

25:13.894 --> 25:21.887
Where the left side of our chart gets in trouble is where the actions of Jesus or the life of Jesus gets separated from what he accomplished on the cross.

25:23.109 --> 25:28.338
The evangelical side of our chart has the tendency to want the king without the kingdom

25:28.482 --> 25:32.667
The mainline side of our chart has a tendency to want the kingdom without the king.

25:33.968 --> 25:40.175
What we see, it's not about doing certain things or living this life in a certain way in order to get right with God.

25:40.595 --> 25:47.663
It's about living out the way of Jesus to bring about God's kingdom because we know we've already been made right with God.

25:49.385 --> 25:55.371
So if we believe Hegel to be right, it's not about thesis or antithesis or laughter, right, or mainline or evangelical.

25:55.692 --> 25:57.874
It's in the synthesis that we find truth.

25:58.050 --> 26:01.474
How do we find the synthesis between the life and the death of Christ?

26:02.435 --> 26:05.198
How do we avoid leaning too far into either directions?

26:05.839 --> 26:09.943
Or how do we avoid just being in the mushy middle and not caring about either of them?

26:11.365 --> 26:20.635
What we see that we need is both orthodoxy and orthopraxia, which are just fancy theological terms for right thinking and right living.

26:21.777 --> 26:26.642
We know this from other areas of our lives, but our beliefs shape our practices.

26:26.882 --> 26:30.187
How we think about something affects how we live it out.

26:31.268 --> 26:39.800
If we look at our chart and our commitment to living in the both end, we could say that right thinking plus right living is this mandourla manifesto.

26:40.621 --> 26:46.670
Our beliefs and our actions they must go together, they are intertwined.

26:47.771 --> 26:52.157
Now for those of you who've been watching the new Star Wars show, Ahsoka, I got an example for you, okay?

26:52.878 --> 26:55.442
We learned about this idea

26:55.618 --> 27:00.505
between the relationship of a teacher and a student in Ahsoka and Sabine.

27:01.145 --> 27:07.574
And they said a relationship between a master and an apprentice is as challenging as it is meaningful.

27:09.036 --> 27:14.043
That the death of Christ is endlessly meaningful to so many things.

27:14.984 --> 27:20.251
But if the life of Christ doesn't challenge us to live differently, does it really matter?

27:21.252 --> 27:22.674
What do we really believe?

27:22.882 --> 27:26.890
If we're not challenged to make our life look different because of it.

27:28.212 --> 27:29.294
And he right puts it like this.

27:29.314 --> 27:39.413
He says, Jesus died for our sins not so that we could sort out abstract ideas, but so that we having been put right could become part of God's plan to put his whole world right.

27:40.095 --> 27:41.938
That is how the revolution works.

27:42.594 --> 27:50.643
These two ideas don't need to be on opposite poles because the truth that emerges in the mandorla, the truth that emerges in the synthesis is this.

27:50.723 --> 27:56.729
It is only because of what was accomplished in the death of Christ that I have any hope of living out the life of Christ.

27:57.811 --> 28:08.402
Only because of what was accomplished in the death of Christ do I have any chance of living out the life of Christ because we have a savior who defeated sin, we can live like our teacher and our master.

28:09.506 --> 28:14.394
When we maintain this perspective, we dodge the misconceptions on both sides of the chart.

28:15.075 --> 28:18.000
On the right, we can move away from avoidance or escapism.

28:18.400 --> 28:22.307
We're not being challenged to live differently because of our faith.

28:23.288 --> 28:31.762
On the left, we move away from work-based righteousness or feeling as if we can change the world without God's help or do it all on our own.

28:32.962 --> 28:45.763
spiritual formation guru Dallas Willard puts it more succinctly than I ever could, which I hate, but he says this, we don't believe something by merely saying we believe it, or even when we believe that we believe it.

28:46.364 --> 28:49.029
We believe something when we act as if it were true.

28:50.892 --> 28:59.506
And that is our hope as we seek to be a both and community in all of these areas on our chart, but especially today,

28:59.586 --> 29:29.586
as we talk about the focus of the life and the death of Christ, that we would believe so deeply about what happened with the death of Christ, that we would act as if it were true by emulating the life of Christ, that we would recognize that we both need a Savior and a teacher, that the revolution would start with us, that as we live out of the death of Christ and into the life of Christ, we would do our part to help bring about God's kingdom today.

29:30.146 --> 29:37.116
that the security that we find in the death of Christ would lead us to live differently, even when it costs us something.

29:38.078 --> 29:46.350
That we wouldn't measure our choices by the ways of the world or how we could get ahead, but rather by how we can best live like Jesus in each and every moment.

29:47.552 --> 29:49.856
That every area of our lives would be different.

29:49.916 --> 29:55.184
Our relationships with each other, our choices at work, our parenting, our voting, our driving.

29:55.745 --> 29:59.410
How we think about violence, our relationship with the earth, whatever it is,

29:59.490 --> 30:03.296
You name it would be different because we're living the life of Christ.

30:04.558 --> 30:06.641
And the world might say that we're weak.

30:07.462 --> 30:14.432
The world might say that we're outdated, that we're gonna get walked all over, that we aren't gonna get ahead or win.

30:14.493 --> 30:26.130
But in spite of those criticisms, we would know that Jesus told us when we choose to live in the light of the life of Christ, we are building on a firm foundation.

30:26.850 --> 30:39.528
that when the waters come, we will be secure, that as we let Jesus invade our lives, everything would be different because of the life that he'd lived and the death that he overcame for himself and for each one of us.

30:40.650 --> 30:51.085
So Antioch family, may we remain committed to both the death of Christ and the life of Christ in our beliefs and in our practices and ultimately in our love.

30:51.765 --> 30:52.146
Amen.

